Obscurity zones.

An obscurity zone is a rectangular area on the map that hides certain entity types from the player's senses while they are standing inside it. Unlike the character blocker, which disables the spier or info menu outright, an obscurity zone leaves both systems running and just filters out the chosen entity types so the world feels harder to perceive without losing access to those features.

Each obscurity zone has a minimum and maximum x and y for its bounds (plus a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), the single player-facing system it affects, a list of entity types it hides or shows, and a whitelist toggle. On 3d maps the zone only applies while the player's z is also inside the zone's z range; on 2d and topdown maps the z gate is bypassed.

Affected system.

A zone affects exactly one system. The build form has a list with two options, the object info menu first and the spier second:

info menu: The zone filters entries out of the object info menu while the player stands inside the zone. Hidden entities don't appear in the list and are not counted in the total objects header. If every entity is hidden, opening the menu speaks there are no objects on the field to view. and bails out instead of opening an empty menu.
spier: The zone filters entries out of the spire reports while the player stands inside the zone. Scanning toward an obscured entity behaves as if that entity is not on the map.

To obscure something from both systems at once, place two overlapping zones, one targeting each system.

Entity types.

Once you pick a system, the build form shows a checkable list of only the entity types that system can actually report, so you never see a choice that would do nothing. The object info menu offers its short list of objects, while the spier offers its longer one.

The object info menu list:

aircraft, bike, door, npc, platform, projectile, security camera, spike, staircase, tts enemie, vehicle, wall.

The spier list:

aircraft, bike, blockage, calendar, checkpoint, clock, conveyor belt, door, elevator, fire, floor breaker, force field, hazard, item, lift, mine, npc, passage, platform, projectile, safe zone, security camera, sensor, sign, spike, switch, teleporter, time bomb, travelpoint, tts enemie, vehicle.

You must tick at least one entity type for the zone to be valid.

Blacklist and whitelist.

Obscurity zones can operate in blacklist and whitelist modes, set by the Enable whitelist checkbox at the bottom of the form.

Blacklist (false): Only the listed entity types are hidden. Everything else stays visible.
Whitelist (true): Only the listed entity types are shown. Everything else is hidden.

So a blacklist zone with door and wall ticked hides doors and walls and shows everything else, while a whitelist zone with the same selection shows only doors and walls and hides everything else.

Position dependence.

Obscurity zones are local. Their effect only applies while the player is standing inside the zone's bounds. Walking out restores the full unfiltered view immediately. This makes it possible to design hallways where the spier goes quiet on traps, rooms where the info menu only lists npcs, or any other localized restriction without disabling spying or the info menu globally.

Overlapping zones.

If multiple obscurity zones overlap and the player is inside more than one at the same time, an entity is hidden if any of the active zones marks it as hidden. So overlapping zones combine their hide rules; an entity stays visible only when none of the active zones hide it.

Authoring obscurity zones by hand.

If you prefer to edit info.sif directly, the on-disk format for an obscurity zone line is: obscurity_zone <minx> <maxx> <miny> <maxy> <affects spier> <affects info menu> <entity types> <whitelist>
For 3d maps insert min and max z right after max y: obscurity_zone <minx> <maxx> <miny> <maxy> <minz> <maxz> <affects spier> <affects info menu> <entity types> <whitelist>

The two bool fields right before the entity list say which systems the zone touches, and they are written as the literal words true or false. The first is affects spier, the second is affects info menu. The entity types are a comma and space separated list, and the final field is the whitelist bool.

The builder only ever writes one of these two bools as true, since each builder zone targets a single system, but a hand-authored line may set them freely:

true false: affects the spier only.
false true: affects the info menu only.
true true: affects both systems at once with a single line. This is the only way to get a both-systems zone without overlapping two zones, and the builder will not produce it, but the game honors it.
false false: affects nothing. The zone sits on the map doing nothing regardless of its entity list or whitelist, since neither system reads it.

Hand-authored lines load the same as builder-authored lines. Note that a hand-authored zone may list entity types the builder would have filtered out for the chosen system, such as a spier-only entity listed on a both-systems line; the unsupported types simply have no effect on the system that cannot report them.
